\emph{For this short-answer question, only the answers (placed in the
boxes) will be marked.}

For the curve \emph{y}\textsuperscript{2} = 5\emph{x}\textsuperscript{4}
- \emph{x}\textsuperscript{2} find d\emph{y}/d\emph{x}.

sols:
Using implicit differentiation we quickly find that

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx}y^2 &= \frac{d}{dx}(5x^4-x^2) \\
2y \frac{dy}{dx} & = 20x^3-2x \\
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{x(10x^2-1)}{y}
\end{align*}

Note that d\emph{y}/d\emph{x} is not defined for \emph{y} = 0.
